    <h1>Dialectic and Historical Reason</h1>

    <p>
      Hegel<span class="sidenote-number">1</span><span class="sidenote">Georg Wilhelm Friedrich Hegel (1770–1831), German philosopher of history and logic. His method of dialectical development—thesis, antithesis, synthesis—describes not a formula but a dynamic process by which concepts unfold historically.</span>
      famously claimed that the owl of Minerva flies only at dusk.
    </p>

    <p>
      This suggests that philosophy—<span class="sidenote-number">2</span><span class="sidenote">i.e., the reflective comprehension of a period or phenomenon—comes too late to shape it; it interprets, but does not guide.</span>—can grasp reality only after the fact.
    </p>

    <p>
      Here's a margin note<span class="marginnote">Margin notes can be used for comments or citations that don't require inline placement. They appear on wider screens and are less intrusive.</span> that doesn’t interrupt the main text.
    </p>

  </article>
